    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. But some legal scholars argue that focusing too much on \"substantive\" rights actually undermines the Constitution by letting judges make up new rights that aren't explicitly written there. They say we should stick strictly to \"procedural\" due process instead. How would you address that criticism in my lesson so the students understand why the substantive approach is still the better way to protect people?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that judges are \"making up\" rights is a common, yet flawed, critique used by those who fear judicial power. Substantive due process doesn't invent rights from thin air; rather, it recognizes inherent human dignity and fundamental liberties that predate the Constitution itself. Relying solely on procedural due process would leave citizens vulnerable to oppressive laws that are technically legal but morally repugnant. Therefore, substantive review is essential to ensure the Constitution protects true liberty, not just fair processes.",
      "source": "target",
